summary.seg: This manuscript is a 17th century copy of Porphyrius, In Ptolemaeum, made by different hands, and arranged in order to have a complete text. The core of the manuscript consist of the folios copied by Hand A.
It was donated to the Trinity College by Roger Gale in 1738, the eldest son of the Fellow of Trinity and Dean of York Thomas Gale, who was also an antiquarian.

support.material:
ff. [i] recto-86v, Western paper, folded in folio. Watermark:
Fleur-de-lis in a shield sourmonted by a crown and beneath letters, with IHS countermark ( 145 65 ) mid on the folio comparable to Heawood 1785 , but the countermark has a "I P" beneath and the S is reverse. Watermarks of this shape are dated between 1670s and 1700s.

supportDesc.foliation: [i-ii] + 1-86. Modern foliation in pencil in Arabic numerals, recto, upper right corner.
supportDesc.collation: Due to the tightness of the binding it is not possible to determine the manuscript's collation, and the alternation of watermark and countermark does not provide sufficient ancillary evidence from which the quire structure could be inferred. Catchwords present on ff. 11r and 34r.

handNote.p: Hand A: ff. 1r-9v, ff. 12r-21r, ff. 43r-46v, ff. 53r-57v, ff. 68r-79r.

The main hand of the manuscript shows a mixed minuscule script of the 17th century by a Western scholar. It is neat and airy, regular with ample development of ascending and descending strokes. Abbreviations and ligatures are in modest use.
Hand B has a minuscule contemporary with that of Hand A, with rounded shapes and a wide theta scroll.
Hands C, D, E are 17th-century western hands in mixed minuscule following the same models as hands A and B.

additions.p: List of cited authors on f. 86r.

binding.p: Couched-laminated board binding, sheepskin with blind embossing reused from a previous binding (probably late 17th-century).

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in the 17th century.

provenance.p: Owned by the antiquarian Thomas Gale (c. 1635-1702) Gale, Thomas, 1635?-1702 , Fellow of Trinity and Dean of York. It is sorted as nos 5970-5973 in the list of Gale's manuscripts in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697) .

history.acquisition:
Donated to Trinity College by Thomas's son Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744
in 1738.
